When I feel the need to enjoy a delicious bacon burger and I don’t want to drive to Zurich then there’s no other option but The Butcher. I have been there only for the takeaway service though. Hence, my experience is based only on this service type.

Atmosphere 2: The restaurant manager (or owner) perfectly pictures the cliché of the low educated Swiss person. He doesn't support the clients if they don't speak Swiss German, and I was forced to ask three times the same question, and in the end, it was a waitress to support and satisfy my request. This guy has to really be thankful to his staff because food and service are great despite his lack of kindness and professionalism.
Place 6: never been there as a guest, I can’t say how it feels to have a meal there. I really like the self-service area with the huge tablets to place your order. Of course, only in German!
Location 6: the restaurant is located in the centre of the town. Easy to reach because it’s close to the train and the bus station and if you are by car, the parking of the Metalli mall makes everything very easy.
Menu 7: a wide range of options for the burgers, both meat and veggie-based. The different bun types can make the difference. The sides are standard but I have to admit, the fries are delicious! I have never explored the chicken-pork burgers because the cheese bacon is the one I always choose.
Service 7: As I wrote before, the staff is the real added value of this place. The crew in the kitchen does a great job and the crew at the restaurant is friendly and professional. It’s a miracle considering the dumb manager...
Bill 6: Prices on average considering the area of the canton Zug.

The second time she said "it's all reserved", when later it was obviously not reserved. Additionally, waitresses are rude and make funny faces when you try to pay in cash. As close to burger perfection as you’re going to get. Best one I had in Switzerland and maybe the best ever. The sauciest meet and most satisfying bun combination. My girlfriend adores the place. Every time she is on a visit we have to check in at the Butcher. On a last visit my better half ordered the Pulled Pork BBQ Burger. Just writing this review I am already salivating.  The pork meat is tender soft it has proper smoked aroma and the Butcher’s Spicy BBQ  Sauce is not really spicy but the mix is nothing short of flawless. Because I like to try new things I ordered Poutine with pulled pork which I never had before. Its like Pulled Pork Burger without a patty instead there is Fries inside. I had to lick my fingers off because the onion sauce was perfect. We topped it off with Chocolate Lava Cake (Schoggi-Chüechli) and Meringue ice cream.

My observation: The food tastes extraordinary. Portions are middle sized. I would prefer that the homemade lemonade would be served directly in the glass not in the plastic bottle.

See you soon!

It is also not possible to reasonably talk to the service personnel and each employee gives different information. So you never know who you can trust.

(Updated, see below) Best burgers in Zug (as of June 2016), though that isn't saying much.
As of now, the place is new and the staff are still finding their feet. That's fine.
The burgers are much like the ones at The Butcher's other locations. They're more off-the-shelf than you would think; there isn't much variation though they do have weekly specials.
The fries are pretty good. Somewhat on the greasy side, but cut from firm potatoes and not sprayed with starch. The seasoning is tasty, if a bit salty.
The burgers would benefit from a slightly thicker patty. They're done medium by default. It's possible to get medium-rare (you'll need to specify "rare"), but that doesn't work very well with their thin patty. The other ingredients are conventional but fresh: no complaints.
For the bun, they should experiment with pretzel dough instead of brioche. But they're good enough for Zug.
Condiments are thin (ketchup is about it, apparently - and you only get that if you ask for it) and sauces are available in small plastic tubs for CHF 1.80 each.
Drinks-wise there is a drinkable house beer on tap (Chopfab).
Dessert means brownie, cheesecake or ice cream. The cake is nothing to write home about. Maybe you'll do better with one of the other options. Coffee is available and it's good.
Summary: a mid-level fast-casual burger joint roughly on par with the Epic Burger franchise in the U.S.
I'm intrigued by the salads on the menu: they look more creative than the burgers.

UPDATE (November 2017): the salads are really good! The service team is friendly and everything runs smoothly. Prompt service, consistent quality of the food.
Overall, The Butcher is probably the best casual-dining option in the Canton of Zug.
